            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 53-year-old Czech woman with a slender build, slightly pale complexion, and a quiet but determined manner. She arrives at the neurology clinic walking with a cane, wearing comfortable flat shoes and a knitted cardigan. She works part-time as a librarian at a municipal library in Brno, a role she has held for over two decades and values deeply for its calm intellectual atmosphere. She lives in a ground-floor flat with her husband and their adult daughter who visits frequently. In her leisure time she enjoys reading historical fiction, tending to her balcony herb garden, and attending a weekly choir rehearsal — though she notes she has had to reduce her singing commitments due to fatigue.\n\n{patientName} reports a fluctuating course of neurological symptoms that have troubled her for more than a decade [MEDLINEPLUS:G35]. She describes episodes of tingling and numbness spreading from her hands into her forearms, occasional \"pins and needles\" sensations in her lower legs and feet [MEDLINEPLUS:G35, MEDDIALOG:G35:2], and intermittent muscle weakness that makes climbing stairs effortful [MEDLINEPLUS:G35]. She also experiences chronic neuropathic pain in her lower extremities, which she describes as a persistent burning quality [SNOMED:G35]. Balance problems and occasional trouble with coordination have led to one near-fall at home in the past year [MEDLINEPLUS:G35].\n\nCognitively, {patientName} mentions word-finding difficulties and occasional memory lapses that have made her work as a librarian more challenging [MEDLINEPLUS:G35]. She also reports intermittent visual disturbances — brief episodes of blurred vision in her right eye — which she attributes to fatigue [MEDLINEPLUS:G35]. Her mood has been affected by the chronicity of her illness; she has been followed by a psychiatrist for depressive symptoms, a well-recognised comorbidity in patients with MS-related neurological burden [PMID:31302591]. She denies any psychotic features.\n\n{patientName} leads a generally sedentary lifestyle due to her symptoms, but tries to walk short distances daily and attends physiotherapy twice a week. She does not smoke and drinks wine only occasionally on social occasions. She maintains close contact with her sister who also has a chronic autoimmune condition, and draws emotional support from her husband and a small circle of long-standing friends."
