            "contentString": "{patientName} was first evaluated for neurological symptoms at age 41, when she presented with an episode of right-sided visual blurring and left-hand numbness that resolved over several weeks [MEDLINEPLUS:G35]. MRI of the brain at that time demonstrated multiple periventricular white-matter lesions consistent with demyelination [MEDLINEPLUS:G35, MEDDIALOG:G35:2]. Lumbar puncture confirmed the presence of cerebrospinal fluid oligoclonal bands [MEDLINEPLUS:G35]. She was diagnosed with relapsing-remitting multiple sclerosis and has been followed in the neurology department ever since [PMID:37966451].\n\n{patientName} has a background of mild depressive disorder, managed with sertraline, diagnosed approximately four years ago in the context of adjustment difficulties related to her MS diagnosis [PMID:31302591]. She also experiences chronic neuropathic pain in both lower limbs for which she takes gabapentin and low-dose amitriptyline [SNOMED:G35]. Baclofen is prescribed for spasticity-related muscle stiffness, a recognised comorbidity in MS [MEDLINEPLUS:G35]. She takes omeprazole for gastroprotection. Atorvastatin was initiated two years ago for mildly elevated cholesterol detected on routine screening.\n\nShe was hospitalised once in 2018 during a significant relapse characterised by severe limb weakness and balance deterioration requiring inpatient physiotherapy rehabilitation [MEDLINEPLUS:G35]. Physical therapy has been an ongoing part of her management [MEDLINEPLUS:G35]. She has a documented allergy to penicillin (urticaria) and a food intolerance to lactose. Family history is notable for her mother having a systemic autoimmune condition and her father having ischaemic heart disease."
